@Context

In '**Red Zenit: An alternative History**' you play as the Danish Social Democrats through the Oil Crisis and transition into late-modern politics. The game is called 'Red Zenit' because in real life the 1970s was the absolute peak of the Danish workers movement. As other historical classes faded, the unity of the workers movement became harder to maintain as internal contradictions was starting to cause division. The working class was now divided between property owners and tenants, as well as public/private workers. 

Can you preserve mass politics while surviving the onslaught of neo-liberalism? Can you leverage the strength of the workers movement to build a socialist majority? 

The aim is for the game to last quite a bit longer than the other ones in the socdem expanded universe (ideally it would last into the early 1990s), with broader demographic changes occuring as a consequence of the players choices while in government. But for now the aim is just to make the game work up until the irl earthquake election of december 1973 as a demo/proof of concept.

